{"type":"message","id":"12c3c6ff","parentId":"fa630c86","timestamp":"2026-05-10T07:02:32.186Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The process is being killed by SIGKILL (signal 9). Exit code 124 means timeout killed it. But the signal shown is SIGKILL (9), not SIGTERM (15). Something is killing the process externally.\n\nWait - actually the process output shows EXIT:124 but that just means timeout exit code. The \"Process exited with signal SIGKILL\" in the process info means the process received SIGKILL, which is why it exited. SIGKILL exit code is 137.\n\nBut wait - the `echo \"EXIT:$?\"` returned 124, meaning the python process exited with 124 (timeout), but then another process that was spawned also showed SIGKILL? This is confusing.\n \nI'm not entirely sure why the process is being killed - could be an OOM issue, the ctranslate2 library hitting an illegal instruction, or something else entirely. Let me try a different approach: load the model and run transcription in a single Python script to avoid module reloading, use smaller beam size and no language restriction to see if that helps. Actually, faster-whisper with int8 compute type might be problematic on WSL2, so maybe I should try int8 float16 or float32 instead.\n\nLet me first check if the WAV file is even being created properly, and try reducing beam_size to 1, limiting max characters per segment to see if it helps.\n","thinkingSignature":"58435b63e20c13b73b7b281bbbd665d18afb5f4928fd585db01e58ff7c0dc6f5"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dc6w3yqz47i8_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -la /tmp/v44.wav && file /tmp/v44.wav && free -m | head -2"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":202,"output":331,"cacheRead":52672,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":53205,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778396532684,"responseId":"064f607600a7c6ae5cfd