{"type":"message","id":"1fb324f6","parentId":"d623ac3b","timestamp":"2026-05-10T07:45:07.755Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, the orphaned processes are gone. The problem is clear now: when `transcribe` is called, even on a short 10s file, it gets killed. But the issue might not be RAM - it's that the `transcribe()` function itself runs too long (longer than whatever timeout is set somewhere).\n\nWait - actually, looking at the kills again. The process is running for about 15-20 seconds then being killed. And the model loads fine. Let me test if `transcribe` with a simple 5s clip works quickly.\n\nActually, I think the issue might be different. Let me look at the `_chunk_audio` function - it calls `ffmpeg` multiple times for longer files, and then for each chunk, it calls `_model.transcribe()`. \n\nWith 3 chunks of 10s each, that's 3 transcription calls, but the real culprit is probably `ffprobe` - I'm running it on every function call to check audio duration, which adds up. And I'm also loading the model repeatedly for each short clip instead of keeping it cached in memory. Looking at the code flow - `_get_audio_duration` calls ffprobe, `_chunk_audio` splits the file into chunks using ffmpeg, then for each chunk it runs the transcription. For a 28s file that's 3 chunks, so ffprobe and 3 ffmpeg calls for splitting, then 3 separate transcription passes. With the model taking 10-15s just to load, I should be testing whether the issue is the loading time itself rather than the transcription process. I see the problem now - the transcription is timing out at around 30 seconds, which is the default exec tool timeout. For a 28-second audio file, even with chunking, the process takes too long because the model load alone eats up 10-15 seconds, then transcription on CPU with int8 takes another 20+ seconds, pushing it past the limit. But the 5-second test also getting killed suggests something else is going on - maybe a memory issue or the process is being terminated for a different reason than just timing out. the process from starting. If the session poll times out but the process is still running, the session gets killed too. So those orphaned processes with 200%+ CPU are likely from previous sessions that timed out - they're still consuming resources even though the session that spawned them is gone.\n\nThis explains why memory keeps declining and why new processes get killed even when the system appears to have RAM available. The real culprit is that multiple Whisper instances are piling up, each consuming over 1GB of memory, and the cumulative effect is starving new processes.\n\nI should verify this by killing all orphaned Python processes and starting fresh with just a single test.\n","thinkingSignature":"312464aaf057f328442609066009d351e2cf99f0dd2c2947474029b2180b0713"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ngde3g44sjtx_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"kill -9 $(ps aux | grep \"python3.*faster\" | grep -v grep | awk '{print $2}') 2>/dev/null; sleep 2; ps aux | grep python3 | grep -v grep; free -m | head -2","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":189,"output":654,"cacheRead":71680,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72523,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778399080735,"responseId":"064f6a6a636208088d41a2a86504b076"}}
