{"type":"message","id":"955f4807","parentId":"041b9310","timestamp":"2026-05-10T07:46:34.112Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The process itself doesn't have specific memory limits. Let me look at the OOM killer more carefully. The dmesg output earlier only showed the boot messages, not recent OOM events. Let me check if there might be a process-specific cgroup.\n\nActually, wait - looking at the earlier `free -m` output, I see:\n- total: 24008 MB\n- available: ~19000-21000 MB\n\nAnd the model is ~1.5 GB. That's not a lot of memory pressure in normal conditions. But the processes that got killed were doing the transcription of 28s audio chunks.\n \nNow I'm reconsidering the cgroup setup from the earlier output - that `/user.slice/user-1000.slice/user@1000.service/app.slice/openclaw-gateway.service` path suggests the gateway service itself is in a cgroup, which could be enforcing memory limits. Maybe the OOM killer is being triggered by the cgroup constraints rather than system-wide memory exhaustion.\n\nLooking at the pattern more carefully - the whisper process gets SIGKILL while the load function succeeds, and this happens consistently with the full 28s audio file but not with shorter chunks. The `av.error.FileNotFoundError` I'm seeing is likely just a side effect where the temp file gets deleted before the audio decoder can read it. So the real question is whether there's a memory limit at the cgroup level that's being hit during the transcription of longer audio.\n","thinkingSignature":"40e2d7bd7ae545452c497f97f9c8a110f796cafe7e02ca5db24d7c20719245b3"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_77368d64shx0_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find /sys/fs/cgroup -name \"memory.limit_in_bytes\" -o -name \"memory.max\" 2>/dev/null | xargs -I{} sh -c 'echo \"{}: $(cat {})\"' 2>/dev/null | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":255,"output":372,"cacheRead":72448,"